amd64_hacker:

Regarding your Unicode Proposal.  First let me thank you for myself and 
the group for your willingness to put your effort and time into this for 
us all. 

I had not found the time to look your proposal in detail previously.  
Here are my thoughts.

First, a couple of minor things:

At the beginning of the proposal, there is a duplicated &quot;with.&quot;

    A caseless, phonetic, left-to-right alphabet optimised for the
    English language (but still useful for other languages with
    similar sounds) created by (Ronald) Kingsley Read.  It is
    the successor to and has much in common with /with/ Shavian.
    Authoritative documentation for it can be found in �EURoeThe
    QuikScript Alphabet�EUR?. [emphasis added]

In the following paragraph under &quot;Alternate Forms,&quot; I suggest changing 
the word &quot;usually&quot; to &quot;highly&quot; since some letters can be properly 
connected and some cannot.

    Many letters have half height or alternate forms in order to help
    speed up writing by reducing the number of strokes and pen lifts.
    The half height and alternate forms are only used in 
�EUR~senior�EUR^(TM)
    QuikScript which is /usually/ cursive. [emphasis added]

Whether a given writer decides to connect any letter to another is his 
choice, but I would consider it improper to extend or change the form of 
a letter in order to make a connection to the next letter possible.  I 
believe the only exceptions approved by Read in the QS manual are for 
the letters with alternate forms (N-o and U-tter) and for F-ee, M-ay and 
TH-ey.

The alternate &quot;TH-ey&quot; extends the bottom of the letter upwards to the 
lower writing line to permit connection with the next letter.  Read 
terms this an &quot;allowable extension,&quot; but it seems to me it should be 
considered an alternate form and listed that way in the proposal.  While 
the end stroke of F-ee can also be extended to join the next letter, 
that seems less important to me so, in my opinion, it could be left out 
of the proposal.  Of course, others may feel that it should be 
included.  I don&#39;t know how difficult it is to include these from a 
technical standpoint.  If we make provision for some alternate forms, 
then adding a couple more is probably no big deal.  In looking back at 
the manual for the first time in a long time, I realize that I almost 
habitually use the alternate form of &quot;M-ay.&quot;  The standard form seems a 
little more difficult for me to write.  That may be lack of practice or 
it may have something to do with being left-handed.

I am confused about your list of letters presented as having half-height 
forms.  You list 15 such letters, but the QS manual lists only P-ea, 
T-ea, H-e, D-ay, Z-oo, and W-ay.  In addition to those, I have used WH-y 
and Y-e for decades since they work as half-letters just as well as the 
six Read suggested.  I had actually forgotten they are not listed in the 
manual as half-letters until Jon Zuck pointed it out to me.  Since it is 
clear what letters they are, it just made sense to me.  Besides, I love 
the way the half-letters contribute to the variety of wordshapes 
possible in QS.  However, you have added seven more:  F-ee, V-ie, S-ee, 
SH-e, J&#39;-ai, CH-eer, J-ay.  I believe this is incorrect.  Can you 
explain how they can be used as half-height forms?

I have never used the two &quot;x&quot; letters as they always struck me as 
outside the spirit of QS -- 1 phoneme to 1 symbol.  It was Read&#39;s stated 
goal for &quot;x&quot; to &quot;compete&quot; with the TO &quot;x&quot; as if that was necessary to 
avoid people deciding that QS was not viable because of two instances 
where it took two QS symbols when only one was needed in TO.  Should &quot;x&quot; 
be included in the proposal.  It is in the manual, and I guess that if 
it is coded, then people can choose whether to use it or not.

I&#39;m impressed with the rest of the proposal.  Thank you again for 
working on this.

Paige


